i## Why I use Gopher	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI like the fact that it's a remote corner of the Internet	/	tilde.team	70
ithat's hard to get to. I think it makes the experience	/	tilde.team	70
iinteresting. It's rare for someone to stumble across a	/	tilde.team	70
iGopher website by chance; you have to be curious and often	/	tilde.team	70
ipassionate.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe community aspect appeals to me, in fact most of the	/	tilde.team	70
iGopher servers currently running are managed by pubnixes,	/	tilde.team	70
iand my files are themselves behind the tilde.pink server.	/	tilde.team	70
htilde.pink	URL:https://tilde.pink	tilde.pink	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI also like the fact that Gopher websites are only consumed	/	tilde.team	70
iby humans, because the companies that scrap the content of	/	tilde.team	70
iwebsites aren't really interested in this protocol. It's too	/	tilde.team	70
ilittle used and it wouldn't be profitable for them.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe Gopher protocol and the documents it carries are very	/	tilde.team	70
ilight. I find it more interesting to concentrate on content	/	tilde.team	70
irather than form, unlike most modern HTML pages which are	/	tilde.team	70
ihighly stylized and carry a lot of elements for the web	/	tilde.team	70
ibrowser to load. For my personal website, I want this	/	tilde.team	70
iworkload to be very low.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI like this simplicity.	/	tilde.team	70
